tät im Alten Ägypten. Teil 2: Die Suche nach dem Individuum im Ägypten der Spätzeit -- tIndividuality versus Collectivity in the Old Testament - Schwache und starke Individualität in alttestamentlichen Schriften -- tResponse auf Jürgen van Oorschot: Zur Einbettung des Individuums in die Welt durch die Reflexion von Resonanzachsen -- tIndividuality vs. Collectivity from a Sociological Perspective -- tIndividuality and Sociality in Ancient Israel -- tResponse to Jan Dietrich: What Is the Origin of Original Thought? -- tIV Categories of Thinking and Ways of Reasoning: Tacit Knowledge, Mentality and Cultural Patterns -- tWisdom: The Rediscovery of a Forgotten Knowledge -- tTacit Knowledge in the Old Testament -- tResponse to Thomas Krüger: What Is the Origin of Original Thought? -- tCultural Patterns in the Old Testament -- tResponse zu Joachim Schaper: Alttestamentliche Mentalitätengeschichte -- tZur Aktivierung alttestamentlicher Paradigmen in der mittelalterlichen Mentalität. Die Sodom-Erzählung und das Hohe Lied -- tResponse zu Peter Dinzelbacher: Zur Methode der Mentalitätsgeschichte -- tList of Contributors -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aResearch into the Hebrew Bible, Ancient Near East, Philosophy and History have long considered whether thought in the cultural area of the ancient Middle East differs from that in the western Mediterranean. The inclusion of neurobiology, psychology, brain research and evolutionary research will widen this horizon and allow new approaches. This volume provides in depth insides into this Archaeology of Mind in 22 contributions.  aSeit langem befassen sich alttestamentliche Exegese, Altorientalistik, Philosophie und Geschichte mit der Frage, ob sich das Denken im Kulturraum des Alten Orients, Ägyptens, Syrien/Kanaans und Israel/Palästinas vom westlichen Mittelmeerraum unterscheidet. Die Einbeziehung von Neurobiologie, Psychologie, Hirn- und Evolutionsforschung ermöglicht neue Ansätze. Die Beiträge dieses Bandes geben einen Einblick in diese Archäologie des Denkens.  aIssued also in print.  afunded by Schweizerischer Nationalfonds (SNF)  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 4aAlter Orient. 4aAspektive. 4aEvolution. 4aHirnforschung. 7aRELIGION / Psychology of Religion.2bisacsh  aAspective.  aWestern thought.  acognition.  aevolution of the brain.1 aAllolio-Näcke, Lars, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllolio-Näcke, Lars, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBauks, Michaela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBehrens, Achim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeyer, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrodersen, Alma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiehl, Johannes Friedrich, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDietrich, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDinzelbacher, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErbele-Küster, Dorothea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFischer, Irmtraud, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrevel, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGehrke, Hans-Joachim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGillmayr-Bucher, Susanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/c